# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prefer NO plaintext passwords on disk
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Build ONE private .secrets.env with KEY=value lines — same file for everything:
#      • Django admin: BETA_DJANGO_ADMIN_USERNAME / BETA_DJANGO_ADMIN_PASSWORD (and PROD_* if you use prod).
#      • Jupyter notebooks: BETA_JUPYTER_PASSWORD / PROD_JUPYTER_PASSWORD (for run_helper_updater / run_base64_updater).
#    Optional URLs only (no secrets): BETA_JUPYTER_URL, PROD_JUPYTER_URL (see Jupyter block below).
# 2. Encrypt the same file:  bash setup_secrets.sh
#    When asked, you may delete the plain .secrets.env (Y) — all those keys then live only inside .secrets.enc.
# 3. Decryption key for .secrets.enc (needed by Flask, pipeline, and Jupyter scripts in NON_INTERACTIVE) — pick ONE:
#    • SECRETS_DECRYPTION_KEY= same passphrase as setup_secrets.sh (one line in .secrets.env if you keep a thin plain file), or
#    • Project file .secrets.key (one line, chmod 600), or
#    • export SECRETS_DECRYPTION_KEY before running.
# 4. Thin .secrets.env after delete: keep admin URLs + SECRETS_DECRYPTION_KEY or rely on .secrets.key; decrypt fills missing Django + Jupyter vars at runtime.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional: public-ish URLs only (no passwords). Safe to keep locally; still gitignored.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
BETA_DJANGO_ADMIN_URL=https://nkb-backend-ccbp-beta.earlywave.in/admin/
PROD_DJANGO_ADMIN_URL=https://nkb-backend-ccbp-prod-apis.ccbp.in/admin/

# --- Django admin (same encrypt workflow as Jupyter: all in one .secrets.env, then setup_secrets.sh) ---
# Do not put real passwords in THIS example copy; in your real .secrets.env (never commit) use real values:
# BETA_DJANGO_ADMIN_USERNAME=
# BETA_DJANGO_ADMIN_PASSWORD=
# PROD_DJANGO_ADMIN_USERNAME=
# PROD_DJANGO_ADMIN_PASSWORD=

# --- Jupyter (same file, same encryption — run_helper_updater.sh / run_base64_updater.sh read from env or decrypted .secrets.enc) ---
# Or keep Jupyter passwords ONLY in secrets.local.env (gitignored *.local.env) so .secrets.env stays URL-only / safe to share.
# Do not put real passwords in this example file.
# BETA_JUPYTER_URL=https://3.111.135.132:2222/notebooks/LoadHelperCode_to_FunctionBased.ipynb
# PROD_JUPYTER_URL=https://3.111.135.132:9944/notebooks/LoadHelperCode_to_FunctionBased.ipynb
# BETA_JUPYTER_PASSWORD=
# PROD_JUPYTER_PASSWORD=
# Optional alias for beta only (same meaning as BETA_JUPYTER_PASSWORD):
# JUPYTER_PASSWORD=
# Playwright needs a /notebooks/... URL with cells, not only /tree.

# Optional: if evaluation metrics admin URL 404s in your environment
# DJANGO_EVAL_METRICS_MODEL_PATH=nkb_question/codingquestiontestcaseevalutionmetrics/

# Required for .secrets.enc if you do NOT use .secrets.key (teammates: uncomment and set — private repo only):
# SECRETS_DECRYPTION_KEY=same-passphrase-as-setup_secrets.sh
# SECRETS_DECRYPTION_KEY_FILE=/path/to/keyfile
